</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Amy Calthrop was born about 1474, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas Calthrop and Alice Hawes. She had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Robert Jennison."},"et":{"abt 1474–":"umbes 1474–Surnud","1474–Female":"1474–Surnud","1471–Male":"1471–Surnud","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","1492–Female":"1492–Surnud","1494–Male":"1494–Su